Say I had a time domain signal x[k]x[k] wich is sparse: log(N)2log(N)2 nonzero samples and the fourier transform has only a very (very!) small number of high frequency components. Are there any techniques or algorithms for recovering these high frequency components in sublinear time? (something like O(kclog(N)d)O(kclog(N)d) where kk is a variable related the sparsity in either the frequency or the time domain).

Expert consensus and history

This interpretation is mine alone, and is at odds with the rest of expert community, as far as I know. Specifically, "redistribution" isn't presented elsewhere, and "time-shift denial" contradicts established narrative. If others also say it, I'm happy to be informed.

In the following I present what history I know that includes my interactions with top scattering researchers and students of Stephane Mallat (who invented scattering).

The "shift-invariance" narrative includes both, exact invariance over TT, and approximate. I present and refute both.

I joined Kymatio efforts to implement JTFS in March 2021, ended up implementing it almost entirely myself, and parting ways later. I spent around a year in their Discord and Github, where I spoke with Vincent Lostanlen, Michael Eickenberg, Edouard Oyallon, and Joakim Anden. I discussed by far the most with Vincent, sometimes productively, and I'm grateful for his overall efforts.

(A): TT is about shift-invariance, and (t)(t)'s time support

(1) Vincent and Michael were surprised to see TT in relation to (t)(t) in a plot. Others either didn't see or didn't comment.

(2) Vincent claimed scattering is invertible within a global time shift TT. This would obviously follow from scattering being invariant to global time shifts by TT.

(3) One of them (I won't name) reasoned, in context of explaining TT, essentially, "Gauss is infinite support, so...". Even after the notion of "effective support" was mentioned.

(4) Joakim and Mallat's Deep Scattering Spectrum refers to TT as "support", and writes

As I show in Appendix A, their subsampling is off by a factor of 4 to avoid aliasing if we remain faithful to code's intent, or by 2 if following the paper's narrative. Their TT is motivated and defined in time domain, and is stated to measure shift-invariance, and never anything else. Temporal variability invariance is neither mentioned nor is their TT compatible with it.

(5) MATLAB concurs with (4). I ran an identical investigation on MATLAB's waveletScattering and found subsampling off by a factor of x1.6-2 (depending on configuration); depending on one's standards, the 1.6 isn't really off. However, TT isn't the subsampling factor (off by x4 on how much it should subsample). I also directly confirmed with its author that TT is meant to denote support (which it does implement faithfully), and is meant to impose shift-invariance.

(6) Mallat's founding paper, Group Invariant Scattering, mentions neither TT nor "scale of invariance", and all key theorems are derived for T=T=.

There's only JJ, and two statements on invariance: (A) simple integration (global time averaging, T=T=) is translation invariant. That's true in every sense. (B) Windowed scattering (non-global) converges to global scattering as JJ (and note it's always taken T=2JT=2J), which to me is a trivial restatement of (A) but it takes proving. The only other description is that "convolution with J(t)J(t) localizes the scattering transform over spatial domains of size proportional to 2J2J".

To those familiar with scattering, none of this is news. My goal isn't just to show it's not a "mis-speech", but that the established position contradicts and is incompatible with my own.

Worth mentioning, there is acknowledging of variability reduction by scattering (e.g. Irene Waldspurger), but it's a long shot from my full take, and discussion of "redistribution" is still absent. Finally,

(7) The Kymatio paper makes no descriptions about TT. Also, some of the mentioned Kymatio members referred to TT's mapping to (t)(t)'s sigma as a "magic number", numerous times, and at least one expressed regret.

All considered, Kymatio's TT matching mine is explained by one of the two: pure coincidence, or deliberate tying of TT to the subsampling factor that avoids aliasing. If latter, clearly not everyone was on same page. ScatNet already sought to avoid aliasing, but perhaps they simply made an error. Either way, alias avoidance is a common discretization technical point with no further interpretation; the Kymatio docs still spoke of "scale of invariance", and nothing else.

None of these works point to my theoretical justification, and of course contradict it on shift-invariance. Thus I say "my definition", even if I took the code straight out of Kymatio.

(B): The shift-invariance is approximate

(1) Deep Scattering Spectrum calls the spectrogram shift-invariant:

and

Here, two specs are introduced: (a) the "invariance" is approximate, (b) the invariance is over an interval much smaller than TT.

(a) is at best sloppy terminology. (b) is one of two things: (1) false advertising, in that subsequent descriptions write "invariance on order of TT"; (2) not pertaining to scattering, only to spectrogram.

Concerning (b2), it's true of neither. It's much worse for STFT in that the spectrum of spectrogram is unbounded, unlike scattering's. Lowpassing isn't CWT's replacement for STFT's fixed resolution, it's an upgrade, for sought-after purposes.

(C): The shift-invariance is exact

(1) "Shift-invariance". It's in the name.

It's true that, I've not seen anywhere written that it's exact, except of course in the name itself.

Some may argue, it's a benign engineering stub. Here I remind, A2: a top scattering researcher, with a Ph. D thesis that extends time scattering, and a dozen of publications on scattering, believed that scattering is strictly shift-invariant by TT. If that's not a case for awful framing, I don't know what is.

There's a simple explanation to the phenomenon. "Scattering", as developed by Mallat, is shift-invariant. What Mallat called "windowed scattering" was shortened to "scattering" in practice, yet there's far fewer theorems for windowed scattering. It makes intuitive sense to think, with an appropriately defined TT, a Gaussian blur imposes at least approximate shift invariance. And,

(2) ScatNet tests (test/, unittest/) and Kymatio11 tests have no tests for shift-invariance.

So, the line of reasoning ended at that broad intuition. When I opened a Github Issue in Kymatio on Measuring invariants, the response wasn't definitive and it has changed. Later I wrote such a test, based on referenced Mallat's equations. They clearly showed relative distance far above invariance. Vincent's statement on "invertibility within shift TT" came after.

So, even if one acknowledges that the invariance isn't exact, it's not enough to stop thinking of its implications as if it were exact. In absence of loud and clear clarification where the term is used, terminology "sloppiness" is better described as "abuse".

1: That's at the time. Now there is a test, mine.

Rebuttal: (A), (C)

Here.

Rebuttal: (B)

(2) We note another piece, from Deep Scattering Spectrum:

Indeed the paper is very consistent in writing "locally". It's never explicitly defined, but there's two interpretations: (a) scattering is invariant to local shifts, i.e. T<T<; (b) scattering is locally invariant to local shifts.

Once (a) is shown, (b) automatically follows, since "locally invariant" just means the measure is applied over a subset of the signal, and any such subset is also a standalone signal. Still, I show it for each.

(a) is shown here. To reinforce the case, consider a signal with a segment that's just a zero-padded unit impulse, and pad length is greater than the effective support of all filters. If unit impulse is somehow an "exception" (which already invalidates the claim), this shows that the local measure can also fail.

I will now show (b). For this I define two distance measures, D1d()D1d() and D2d()D2d(), described in Appendix B. In summary, D1dD1d is so we get an idea of the best case, worst case, and average scenario of distances due to shifts, on per-coefficient basis. D2dD2d is so we get an idea of what happens with the entire scattering output over a time interval. D1dD1d is more for "debug info", D2dD2d is what "locally invariant" would actually mean.

Below are results for clean audio (librosa.load(librosa.ex('trumpet'))), first & second order scattering, with signal length N=32768N=32768 samples, lowpass T=NT=N (following ScatNet's definition), and shift c=T/4c=T/4. The window of measurement (i.e. 0,10,1) is over [T/4,NT/4][T/4,NT/4] with respect to the input (which spans [0,N][0,N]), to be more favorable11:

  • Blue, orange, green = max, min, and mean.
  • Red horizontal line = goal, relative Euclidean distance of 0.010.01.

The orange curve on right may look like success, but it's the best case scenario. The claim by scattering is for the blue curve to be below the red line (rather, purple, but idea's worst case).

Now with c=T/40c=T/40, with only the favorable interval:

The best case succeeds, the worst case (of the already favorable case) doesn't. Now T/400T/400:

Finally, success.

So, for a 1 minute signal, if we want invariance over 1 second, we require a lowpass over 6.7 minutes. After "invariance" is clarified, some users may be content with 0.10.1 as the distance threshold instead of 0.010.01; then we require a lowpass over 40 seconds.

Here I went out of my way to make the best possible pragmatic case in favor of shift-invariance. There's also dependence on the quality factor, which I've also chosen favorably. If there's temptation to use a different threshold for validation, just a reminder that a top scattering researcher was fooled.

There is no shift-invariance. There is shift-insensitivity, and that's already good.

1: in short, the main driver of distance due to shifts is whether unaveraged coefficients are locally time-limited. So, stay clear of edges, which expose finiteness

If there is some TT for any cc, why not just use that?

As mentioned earlier, the resulting lowpass is tremendous relative to cc. This introduces three problems:

  1. Avoiding boundary effects will require padding by x10+ the input's length for most cc, skyrocketing compute expense
  2. The loss of information due to unpadding grows
  3. The TT to cc relationship breaks down for T>kNT>kN (kk depends on how TT is defined), per finiteness of xx and log behavior of Gaussian (as described here TODO), and the TT requirement quickly begins to shrink. This means that for some large c0c0, invariance to 2c02c0 is achieved with much less than 2T2T. It makes distances due to 2c02c0 quite close to qualifying for the same threshold of "invariance", such that there's no meaningful difference between being invariant to c0c0 and 2c02c0. This also makes it difficult to target a given cc past some point. At that point it makes the most sense to go straight for global averaging and achieve actual and total shift-invariance. That "point" is T=4NT=4N per ScatNet (rather 4.24), and T=NT=N per my library.

Side-point: warp-stability

Vincent claimed to me, and in his Ph.D dissertation, that warp stability is conditional upon QQ.

Joakim and Mallat in DSS claim it's conditional upon TT.

I disagree with both. The line of reasoning for both these claims is perfectly consistent with that of "scale of invariance": the idea that there's some sharp cutoff, a discontinuous behavior, in the very deliberately smooth Gaussian lowpass filter.

Mallat's GIS claims neither; it's possible Mallat glossed over Joakim's claim. Joakim and Mallat also haven't replied to my e-mail request for clarification. I followed Mallat's derivation of warp stability in full; I'll spare showing it all, but there's no mention of QQ or TT, except in the way I had suspected:

hh refers to the filterbank, and CC is the constant of proportionality in the theorem. Indeed, the upper bound has proportionality dependence on QQ and TT, as these control the widths of the filters. The theorem doesn't "stop working" past a certain shift TT or warp QQ, it just stops being useful. It only stops working in the exact criterion mentioned in the theorem, which does correspond to discontinuous behavior: time reversal.

Appendix A

Striding by "half overlap" already sounds off, worst case if TT denotes support, but we can't tell from text alone. Looking into ScatNet code (which the paper's linked site points to), we see sigma0 defined more than 10 times as liberally as in Kymatio. This alone isn't enough as there's further modifications, so we inspect the lowpass filter (in frequency, trimmed) and the output directly:

Filter length is 32768, so per my definition, this lowpass is T32768/128=256T32768/128=256. Signal length is 16384. ScatNet's output length is 88, my definition's is 16384/T=6416384/T=64.

Since I've not fully understood the code, to be absolutely sure there's no other explanation, I check the first order impulse response (in time) with maximum oversampling - ScatNet vs my library:

Skipping some steps ahead, I reproduced ScatNet's (t)(t) in my library, and more precisely, it has T=483T=483. Length 8 output requires 16384/8=204816384/8=2048: a x4.24 mismatch. ScatNet is subsampling by 4 on a full-band signal!

Lastly, we check what it looks like in time domain. Here we must distinguish between what TT should be (according to me) and what ScatNet thinks it is - to which we refer to the cited excerpt. It strides by T/2T/2 instead of by TT, and indeed the code defaults to (which is what the paper uses) oversampling=1. ScatNet vs mine:

Hence TT isn't the effective support either. It really doesn't fall under any precise metric. My best shot at reading intent:

  1. "half overlapping" is motivated by the STFT rule of thumb, which would make TT a very liberally (but not outlandishly) thresholded effective support. Also note that in some applications it's acceptable to call "cutoff" -3dB, which is 0.71, which I do consider outlandish here, so by that standard their "support" is far safer.
  2. That it's called "oversampling", firstly, disqualifies TT as the subsampling factor, but is also either plain wrong or assumes an excessively liberal expected input bandwidth.
  3. The paper does state intent of "avoiding aliasing", yet later cites aliasing as the main source of error in inversion, meaning it's really "reducing" aliasing (i.e. making it far from negligible).
  4. The paper repeatedly writes "duration on order of TT", implying a time-domain definition.
  5. And of course, the paper heavily touts shift-invariance, and measures it by TT: "The interval of time-shift invariance is defined by the size of the time averaging window ", and "scattering transform ... is computed along time, over half-overlapping windows of size TT". Recall from earlier, that even my much more conservative TT yields completely unacceptable distances for "shift invariance".

Appendix B

D1dSx,Sxc;I,0,1()=stat{rel_l2t{Sx(,t)I(),Sxc(,t)I()}},DSx,Sxc;I,0,11d()=stat{rel_l2t{Sx(,t)I(),Sxc(,t)I()}},
stat() is one of:  inf(), sup(), (), over 01rel_l2t(a,b)=abt/at,I()=(tI)(1)stat() is one of:  inf(), sup(), (), over 01rel_l2t(a,b)=abt/at,(1)I()=(tI)

where the three statstat ("statistics") are simply the max (infimum), min (supremum), and mean of input along ; tt is the L2 norm along tt, |f(,t)|2dt|f(,t)|2dt (which becomes Euclidean distance when applied on a difference); is the rectangle function; and SxSx and SxcSxc are scatterings of x(t)x(t) and x(tc)x(tc).

D2dSx,Sxc;I,0,1()=rel_l2,t{Sx(,t)I(),Sxc(,t)I()},01(2)(2)DSx,Sxc;I,0,12d()=rel_l2,t{Sx(,t)I(),Sxc(,t)I()},01

These look fairly complicated, but the idea is simple - distances over subintervals:

  • In (1)(1), we compute distance over a time interval of size II, for every 1D scattering coefficient with center frequency (or path) separately. This time interval is centered over every point from 00 to 11 (a sweep). In code, that's rel_l2(a[:, slc], b[:, slc]), where slc = slice(tau - interval//2, tau + interval//2). The result is a 2D array, as in out[lambda, tau]. Then we compute one of the statistics over tau, e.g. out = max(out, axis=1).
  • In (2)(2), we do a 2D version of this without a "stats" (summarizer) function, instead rel_l2 is taken over a 2D slice: so instead of a and b, which are 1D slices of Sx and SxT, we do Sx[:, slc] and SxT[:, slc].
